My decision to leave was a culmination of experiences and truth finding that actually made it easy to part ways. I always doubted men were called of God. It wasn’t difficult for me to see those that aspired to callings and mingled their own beliefs with a Christ centered teaching. Over the decades. I would see the damage it caused to my family and no questions asked responses from the brethren. CES letter was the cherry on top for me.

Throughout my time in the church, I was always convinced I wasn't good enough and that I was an awful person. I compensated for this by being a misogynist and having a holier-than-thou attitude, only to realize I was hurting those around me, whilst being hurt by the lies I was being spoonfed by the church. My faith was first tested when I noticed loopholes in the repentance system: You could sin, and repent, then sin, then repent again. It was like a get out of jail free card. I then decided to test the limits of this and began pushing the limits of it. My faith crisis was only pushed forward after the actions of a primary teacher. I&mldr;

In 2017, my wife and I had a severe falling-out with our Mormon bishop. I went online for help and went down the rabbit hole. This resulted in a faith crisis then a faith transition. Eventually, I resigned from the Mormon church in 2022. Link to my resignation essay: https://www.reddit.com/r/ExitStories/comments/18kh7p6/why_i_resigned/

ceyre

My struggles with church started when I met friends who were gay for the first time. I learned about being gay, being trans, and saw the way my friends were abused and punished by a church I thought cared about them. Then it was my turn. After discovering I was Trans, everything began to fall apart. My parents had made their stance on Transgender people very clear: They didn't exist. Any ideas of Transgender identity were merely temptation, confusion, mental illness, or possession by the devil himself. I struggled for years to hide it from my parents but the more I hid the more I saw my health decline, and the more resentment built. I fell down rabbit holes of&mldr;

I wondered why, if this is so great, why doesn’t everyone embrace it? What am I missing and why does the Church make me feel empty? Why would a loving God treat his children so differently based on where they were born, who their parents are, what race they were born into, what their last name is, what their sexual preference is, what their gender is, how much money they have and whether they followed Hindu, Buddhist, Muslim or Christian teachings. Why would God demand 10% tithing to get into the celestial kingdom; pay-to-play just didn’t seem right. Why would God pick Joseph Smith since he’s such a schmuck. Polygamy …. Really? What woman would embrace a role of making&mldr;

